article.headline: T-Wolves happy for a change with fourth quarter
article.linkText: Timberwolves finish strong to nip Suns
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- For the first time in weeks, the Minnesota Timberwolves were pleased with their play in the fourth quarter. Kevin Garnett had 32 points and 11 rebounds to lead the Timberwolves to a 108-104 win over the Phoenix Suns on Saturday night. Chauncey Billups had 19 points and 11 assists for Minnesota. Wally Szczerbiak added 19 points. Shawn Marion scored 17 of his 20 points in the second half for the Suns, who lost for the fourth time in five games. Stephon Marbury started the game on the bench because of a sore left ankle, but contributed 23 points. Jake Voskuhl scored a career-high 20 for the Suns, whose reserves outscored their starters 61-43. Trailing 106-102, the Suns closed the gap after Jake Tsakalidis tipped in a missed shot with 11.1 seconds left. Then, Marion stole Joe Smith's inbounds pass and had a chance to tie the game. But Smith redeemed himself by blocking Marion's shot and Billups was fouled after picking up the loose ball. "I didn't want him to score at all," Smith said. "I was upset with myself." "If he didn't block it, it was going in," Marion said. "It's just one of those things. Coach tells us to always finish the game, play to the end." Billups made both free throws with 7.2 seconds left to seal the win. "That's the way we should play in the fourth quarter, that's what I'm talking about," Szczerbiak said. For the Wolves, who have won just two of their last nine games by double figures, aggressive play in the fourth quarter was a welcome change. Phoenix shot 53.8 percent from the field, but the Wolves, who have struggled offensively in the fourth quarter, shot 13-for-18 from the field in the period. They also had 12 assists to Phoenix's five. "We've all got to be aggressive at clutch time," Garnett said. "Last time (in Phoenix), we were too passive. We've got to create energy. No hesitation. All reaction." Minnesota lost 103-100 to the Suns in overtime in February. After trailing most of the game, the Suns seized the lead on the strength of the shooting of Marion, Marbury and Penny Hardaway. The teams traded baskets, and the lead, for much of the fourth quarter. Gary Trent hit a turnaround jumper to give the Wolves a 100-97 lead. Marion answered with a 3-pointer to tie it, but Garnett countered with a dunk at the other end after shaking off Marion. Marbury tied it at 102 after drawing a blocking foul on Smith. Billups, fouled by Marbury, made two free throws with 51.9 seconds left to give Minnesota a 104-102 lead. On the next possession, Hardaway threw the ball away. Garnett hit a turnaround on Bo Outlaw with 15.4 seconds to go. "They got too many offensive rebounds and scored off them," Suns coach Frank Johnson said. "They had a good guy they could go to (Garnett). And Trent, he hit some big shots." Minnesota charged to an early 19-7 lead. But Phoenix exploited the Wolves' weak inside defense to cut the deficit before halftime. Voskuhl scored 17 points in the first half, and Marbury, booed every time he touched the ball, also provided a lift in a reserve role, scoring 13 first-half points. The Suns took their first lead on a jumper by Joe Johnson from the top of the key with 50.4 seconds left in the half. Garnett made four free throws to give the Wolves a 52-49 lead with nine seconds left. But Dan Majerle tied it with a 3-pointer at the buzzer.

Game notes
Marbury did not start for just the second time this season. "He needs surgery. He has some spurs in it," Johnson said of Marbury's ankle. "He's been fighting this all year." Marbury said he plans on playing in all of Phoenix's remaining games. "I'm going to rest tomorrow and Monday and see how it is," he said. Milt Palacio started in Marbury's place. ... Phoenix's loss Friday night at Indiana assured the Suns of a losing season, the first in Majerle's 14-year career. The Suns needed to win their remaining games to avoid their worst season since 1987-88 when they went 28-54.
